The primary transportation needs and deficiencies in the project corridor are summarized
 Increase Capacity: Provide additional capacity in the corridor to meet traffic
 Improve Traffic Operations: Provide geometric improvements on the roadway and
at intersections to provide adequate operations.
 Improve Safety: Reduce crash rates within the corridor.
 Improve Roadway Pavement Structure: Improve the roadway pavement within the
 Provide bicycle and pedestrian accommodations within the corridor.
 Enhance transit accommodations within the corridor.
 Address geometric deficiencies of the roadway shoulders.

page.text: Review of the 2007‐2009 crash history revealed that there were 77 crashes along the corridor
during the three‐year period. Over half (55 percent) of the eleven analyzed intersections within
the corridor exceed the MnDOT Metro District average crash and/or severity rates. It is also
noteworthy that rear‐end crashes made up over 48 percent of all crash types, with five
Avenue)) having rear‐end collisions account for at least 62 percent of all crashes. Rear‐
end crashes are often associated with sudden deceleration by the first car and not enough time
to brake for the second car, resulting in a collision. At uncontrolled intersections, this can arise
with the sudden entry of a vehicle into the major roadway traffic stream without an acceptable
gap in traffic. At signalized intersections, rear‐end collisions often are the result of congested
conditions where there is frequent starts and/or stops in traffic. For more information, refer to
Technical Memorandum: CSAH 51 Access and Crash Summary in Appendix F.

Anoka County's 2030 Transportation Plan includes a goal to "strengthen the existing
multimodal transportation system to facilitate increased connectivity between transportation
modes." Portions of CSAH 51 between CSAH 12 and CSAH 14 have a trail and/or a segment of
sidewalk, but there is not a fully connected route for either facility type. In addition, within or
immediately adjacent to the CSAH 51 corridor are three schools, which are traditional bicycle
and pedestrian trip destinations. Each of these school sites also has recreational park facilities
that are used by corridor and neighborhood residents. Currently, there is not a continuous
bicycle/pedestrian facility on either side of CSAH 51.
On the west side of CSAH 51, there are approximately 1.3 miles of disconnected sidewalk or
trail segments between CSAH 12 and CSAH 14. On the east side of CSAH 51 there is less than
0.80 mile of sidewalk or multi‐use trail facilities. The lack of a continuous sidewalk or trail on
either side of the roadway results in pedestrians and bicyclists needing to cross CSAH 51
numerous times to traverse the entire corridor.
In reviewing crosswalks and pedestrian ramps, it was determined that the majority of those
provided are not compliant with current Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) requirements.

page.text: In addition to multi‐use paths, the more experienced bicyclists prefer to ride on roadway
shoulders. In the case of the CSAH 51 corridor, there are areas where neither satisfactory
roadway shoulders nor multi‐use trails exist, thereby limiting options for safe bicycle travel. For
more information, refer to Technical Memorandum: Roadway Deficiencies and
The CSAH 51 corridor is served by two fixed transit routes, Metro Transit Route 59 and Anoka
Traveler Route 831. Both of these routes operate during the AM and PM peak travel periods
and are primarily used by commuters living within the corridor. Within the corridor, there are a
total of sixteen transit stops (eight southbound and eight northbound). Of these, only eight are
adjacent to a sidewalk or multi‐use trail. The other stops are located adjacent to the road and
are accessible to pedestrians only by walking along the road. During the winter when snow
accumulates in these areas, accessing these stops is difficult and potentially dangerous.
In the event of an emergency, traffic‐stop, or vehicle‐breakdown a roadway shoulder provides
motorists a safe area to get out of the flow of traffic. Shoulders, especially paved or hard
shoulders, also increase road safety as they allow some extra space should a motorist need to
take evasive action or need to recover control of their vehicle before a run‐off road (ROR)
collision occurs. Shoulders are also used by more experienced bicyclists as a travel lane. On
CSAH 51, there are approximately three‐quarters of a mile of roadway without an adjacent

page.text: Several potential improvement options were reviewed in the analysis of alternatives performed
for this project. While some of these options were rejected since they did not meet the
project’s purpose and needs, some were considered but rejected for Social, Environmental, and
Economic (SEE) impacts or other reasons. The options that were considered are summarized
This alternative entails a cross section that is rural or uses ditches to collect and distribute
stormwater runoff. The rural ditch section requires an approximately eight‐feet wide by 3.75
feet deep ditch along each side of the roadway, which would make the overall corridor 16 feet
wider than it wood as an urban section with curb and gutter. As such, the rural section would
have more right of way and wetland impacts compared to the urban section. Because the
urban section would be able to collect and distribute stormwater within a smaller area, thereby
resulting in fewer right of way impacts, the urban section is preferred over a rural section.
It is anticipated that a minimal amount of right of way will be required along the CSAH 51
corridor if the expanded roadway and off‐street trails remain centered within the existing
corridor. However, shifts in the alignment of CSAH 51 were considered to avoid impacts to an
Environmental Justice (EJ) area, a Section 4(f) Resource, and an electrical substation adjacent to
CSAH 51. Alignment shifts to the east (Alternative 2a) and west (Alternative 2b) were evaluated
to determine impacts to these areas or properties.

willing sellers and preferred to be acquired rather than stay in the homes. Property owners and
tenants indicated that existing traffic on the corridor is loud and they anticipate that it will get
worse as more vehicles continue to use the roadway. Additionally, owners indicated that it is
challenging to get into and out of their driveways due to the amount of traffic on the corridor.
A number felt unsafe trying to get in and out. Even if the roadway was expanded to the west,
the property owners indicated that noise would continue to be a problem and getting into and
out of driveways would get worse.
The county has assisted with the relocation of the affected homeowners and tenants following
the Uniform Relocation Assistance and Real Property Acquisition Policies Act of 1970, as
amended and 49 CFR Part 24. This assistance has included meeting with affected residents to
look at new properties, assisting with the purchase or rental of new properties, compensation
for relocation fees, and inspection of new properties to ensure the safety and sanitation is
satisfactory. Of the nine properties that are being acquired, seven are homeowner‐occupied
and two are rentals. Five owners of the homeowner‐occupied residences have already worked
with the county to find and purchase new homes. The new homes are in better condition and
are comparable in size, if not larger than, the old homes. One of the remaining two
homeowner‐occupied residents has chosen to move to their lake property while they decide if
they want to purchase a new home. The remaining homeowner is currently working with the
county to find a new property to purchase. Tenants of the two rental properties were also
assisted in finding new rentals and compensated for moving expenses. One of the tenants was
already searching for new housing prior to being aware of the project.

There are several laws that regulate activity within wetland areas with the intent to preserve
wetland areas, water quality and wildlife habitat among other important wetland functions.
Section 404 of the Clean Water Act, at the federal level, is implemented by the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers and requires applicants to document avoidance and minimization of impacts prior
to approving a permit to mitigate impacts. Due to federal funds being applied to this project it
also is required to comply with Executive Order 11990, which states that all federal projects
must demonstrate that there are no practicable alternatives to construction in wetlands.
At the state level, there is the Public Waters Work permit that is implemented by the
Minnesota DNR for waters that are identified on the Public Waters Inventory (PWI).
Additionally, there is the Wetland Conservation Act, which is implemented by the City of Coon
Rapids and the Coon Creek Watershed District (CCWD) for the City of Blaine. Oversight and
review is provided by the Technical Evaluation Panel (TEP).
